# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:bevy-engine/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] In computing, **data-oriented design** is a program optimization approach motivated by efficient usage of the CPU cache, often used in video game development.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] The approach is to focus on the data layout, separating and sorting fields according to when they are needed, and to think about transformations of data.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] Proponents include Mike Acton, Scott Meyers, and Jonathan Blow.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] The parallel array (or structure of arrays) is the main example of data-oriented design.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] It is contrasted with the *array of structures* typical of object-oriented designs.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] The definition of data-oriented design as a programming paradigm can be seen as contentious as many believe that it can be used side by side with another paradigm, but due to the emphasis on data layout, it is also incompatible with most other paradigms.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] These methods became especially popular in the mid to late 2000s during the seventh generation of video game consoles that included the IBM PowerPC based PlayStation 3 (PS3) and Xbox 360 consoles.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] Historically, game consoles often have relatively weak central processing units (CPUs) compared to the top-of-line desktop computer counterparts.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] This is a design choice to devote more power and transistor budget to the graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] For example, the 7th generation CPUs were not manufactured with modern out-of-order execution processors, but instead use in-order processors with high clock speeds and deep pipelines.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] In addition, most types of computing systems have main memory located hundreds of clock cycles away from the processing elements.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] Furthermore, as CPUs have become faster alongside a large increase in main memory capacity, there is massive data consumption that increases the likelihood of cache misses in the shared bus, otherwise known as Von Neumann bottlenecking.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] Consequently, locality of reference methods have been used to control performance, requiring improvement of memory access patterns to fix bottlenecking.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] Some of the software issues were also similar to those encountered on the Itanium, requiring loop unrolling for upfront scheduling.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] The claim is that traditional object-oriented programming (OOP) design principles result in poor data locality, more so if runtime polymorphism (dynamic dispatch) is used (which is especially problematic on some processors).
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] Although OOP appears to "organise code around data", it actually organises source code around data types rather than physically grouping individual fields and arrays in an efficient format for access by specific functions.
[src:bevy-engine/data-oriented-design] Moreover, it often hides layout details under abstraction layers, while a data-oriented programmer wants to consider this first and foremost.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] ECS prioritizes composition over inheritance.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Every entity is defined not by a type hierarchy, but by the components associated with it.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Systems act globally over all entities that have the required components.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] For example, a food system might iterate through every entity with a relevant component tracking hunger, and act on them to push them a little away from satiation at time intervals.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Entities lacking the component like terrain or items would be naturally ignored by the food system.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Due to an ambiguity in the English language, an interpretation of the name is that an ECS is a system comprising entities and components.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] In the 2002 talk at GDC, Scott Bilas compared a C++ object system and his new custom component system.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] This is consistent with a traditional use of *system* terms in general systems engineering with Common Lisp Object System and type system as examples.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Although mostly found in video game development, the ECS can be useful in other domains, such as in robotics simulators like Gazebo.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] ECS combines orthogonal, well-established ideas in general computer science and programming language theory.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] For example, components can be seen as a mixin idiom in various programming languages.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Components are a specialized case under the general delegation approach and meta-object protocol.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] That is, any complete component object system can be expressed with the *templates* and *empathy* model within The Orlando Treaty vision of object-oriented programming.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] An entity represents a general-purpose object.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] In a game engine context, for example, every coarse game object is represented as an entity.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Usually, it only consists of a unique ID.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] as possessing a particular aspect, and (the component) holds the data needed to model that aspect.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] For example, every game object that can take damage might have a Health component associated with its entity.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] A system is a process that acts on all entities with the desired components.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] For example, a physics system may query for entities having mass, velocity and position components, iterate over the results, and do physics calculations for each entity using the set of components.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] The behavior of an entity can be changed at runtime by systems that add, remove or modify components.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] This eliminates the ambiguity problems of deep and wide inheritance hierarchies often found in object-oriented programming techniques that are difficult to understand, maintain, and extend.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Common ECS approaches are highly compatible with, and are often combined with, data-oriented design techniques.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Data for all instances of a component are contiguously stored together in physical memory, enabling efficient memory access for systems that operate over many entities.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] In 1963, Ivan Sutherland's Sketchpad stored the visual elements of a drawing using an early form of an ECS.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Instead of encapsulating points in different objects (e.g. lines, circles, rectangles) points were stored in a ring buffer, and visual elements were only referencing them.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] When moving a point, this allowed updating all the shapes and constraints using it.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] In 1998, *Thief: The Dark Project* pioneered an ECS.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] The engine was later used for its sequel, as well as *System Shock 2*.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] In 2002, Scott Bilas of Gas Powered Games (Dungeon Siege) gave a seminal talk on ECS.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] This inspired numerous later well-known implementations.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] In early January 2007, Mick West who worked on the Tony Hawk series, shared his experiences on the process of ECS adoption at Neversoft.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Also in 2007, the team working on *Operation Flashpoint: Dragon Rising* experimented with ECS designs, including those inspired by Bilas/*Dungeon Siege*, and Adam Martin later wrote a detailed account of ECS design, including definitions of core terminology and concepts.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] In particular, Martin's work popularized the ideas of systems as a first-class element, entities as identifiers, components as raw data, and code stored in systems, not in components or entities.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] In 2015, Apple Inc. introduced GameplayKit, an API framework for iOS, macOS and tvOS game development that includes an implementation of ECS.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] In October 2018 the company Unity released its megacity demo that utilized a tech stack built on an ECS.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Unity's ECS runs on a powerful optimized architecture known as DOTS, which "empowers creators to scale processing in a highly performant manner".
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] The data layout of different ECS's can differ as well as the definition of components, how they relate to entities, and how systems access entities' components.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Adam Martin defines in his blog series what he considers an Entity–Component–System.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] An entity only consists of an ID for accessing components.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] It is a common practice to use a unique ID for each entity.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Some of these advantages can also be achieved using smart pointers.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Components have no game code (behavior) inside of them.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] The components don't have to be located physically together with the entity, but should be easy to find and access using the entity.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Unity's layout has tables, each with columns of components.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] In this system an entity *type* is based on the components it holds.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] For every entity *type* there is a table (called an *archetype*) holding columns of components that match the components used in the entity.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] To access a particular entity one must find the correct archetype (table) and index into each column to get each corresponding component for that entity.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] The normal way to transmit data between systems is to store the data in components, and then have each system access the component sequentially.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] For example, the position of an object can be updated regularly.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] This position is then used by other systems.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] If there are a lot of different infrequent events, a lot of flags will be needed in one or more components.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Systems will then have to monitor these flags every iteration, which can become inefficient.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] A solution could be to use the observer pattern.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] All systems that depend on an event subscribe to it.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] The action from the event will thus only be executed once, when it happens, and no polling is needed.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] The ECS has no trouble with dependency problems commonly found in object-oriented programming since components are simple data buckets and have no dependencies.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Each system will typically query the set of components an entity must have for the system to operate on it.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] For example, a render system might register the model, transformations, and drawable components.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] When it runs, the system will perform its logic on any entity that has all of those components.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Other entities are simply skipped, with no need for complex dependency trees.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] However, this can be a place for bugs to hide, since propagating values from one system to another through components may be hard to debug.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] ECS may be used where uncoupled data needs to be bound to a given lifetime.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] The ECS uses composition, rather than inheritance trees.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] An entity will be typically made up of an ID and a list of components that are attached to it.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] Any game object can be created by adding the correct components to an entity.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] This allows the developer to easily add features to an entity, without any dependency issues.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] For example, a player entity could have a *bullet* component added to it, which would then meet the requirements to be manipulated by some *bulletHandler* system, which then could result in that bullet doing damage to other objects by running into them.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] The merits of using ECS for storing the game state have been proclaimed by many game developers like Adam Martin.
[src:bevy-engine/entity-component-system] One good example is the blog posts by Richard Lord, where he discusses the merits and why ECS-designed game data storage systems are so useful.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:bevy-engine/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In computer science, **object composition** and **object aggregation** are closely related ways to combine objects or data types into more complex ones.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In conversation, the distinction between composition and aggregation is often ignored.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Common kinds of compositions are objects used in object-oriented programming, tagged unions, sets, sequences, and various graph structures.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Object compositions relate to, but are not the same as, data structures.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Object composition refers to the logical or conceptual structure of the information, not the implementation or physical data structure used to represent it.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] For example, a **sequence** differs from a **set** because (among other things) the order of the composed items matters for the former but not the latter.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Data structures such as arrays, linked lists, hash tables, and many others can be used to implement either of them.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Perhaps confusingly, some of the same terms are used for both data structures and composites.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] For example, "binary tree" can refer to either: as a data structure it is a means of accessing a linear sequence of items, and the actual positions of items in the tree are irrelevant (the tree can be internally rearranged however one likes, without changing its meaning).
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] However, as an object composition, the positions are relevant, and changing them would change the meaning (as for example in cladograms).
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Object-oriented programming is based on using objects to encapsulate data and behavior.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] It uses two main techniques for assembling and composing functionality into more complex ones, sub-typing and object composition.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Object composition is about combining objects within compound objects, and at the same time, ensuring the encapsulation of each object by using their well-defined interface without visibility of their internals.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In this regard, object composition differs from data structures, which do not enforce encapsulation.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Object composition may also be about a group of multiple related objects, such as a set or a sequence of objects.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Delegation may enrich composition by forwarding requests or calls made to the enclosing composite object to one of its internal components.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In class-based and typed programming languages, types can be divided into composite and non-composite types, and composition can be regarded as a relationship between types: an object of a composite type (e.g.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] *car*) "has" objects of other types (e.g.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] When a composite object contains several sub-objects of the same type, they may be assigned to particular roles, often distinguished by names or numbers.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] For example, a **Point** object might contain 3 numbers, each representing distance along a different axis, such as 'x', 'y', and 'z'.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] The study of part-whole relationships in general, is mereology.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Composition must be distinguished from subtyping, which is the process of adding detail to a general data type to create a more specific data type.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] For instance, cars may be a specific type of vehicle: *car* is a *vehicle*.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Subtyping doesn't describe a relationship between different objects, but instead, says that objects of a type are simultaneously objects of another type.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] The study of such relationships is ontology.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In prototype-based programming languages such as JavaScript, objects can dynamically inherit the behaviors from a prototype object at the moment of their instantiation.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Composition must be distinguished from prototyping: the newly instantiated object inherits the composition of its prototype, but it may itself be composed on its own.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Composite objects may be represented in storage by co-locating the composed objects, by co-locating references, or in many other ways.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] The items within a composite object may be referred to as *attributes*, *fields*, *members*, *properties*, or other names, and the resulting composition as *composite type*, *storage record*, *structure*, *tuple*, or a *user-defined type (UDT)*.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] For details, see the aggregation section below.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In UML modeling, objects can be conceptually composed, independently of the implementation with a programming language.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] The relationship between the aggregate and its components is a weak "has-a" relationship: The components may be part of several aggregates, may be accessed through other objects without going through the aggregate, and may outlive the aggregate object.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] The state of the component object still forms part of the aggregate object.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Thus in UML, composition has a more narrow meaning than the usual object composition.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Aggregation differs from ordinary composition in that it does not imply ownership.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In composition, when the owning object is destroyed, so are the contained objects.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In aggregation, this is not necessarily true.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] For example, a university owns various departments (e.g., chemistry), and each department has a number of professors.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] If the university closes, the departments will no longer exist, but the professors in those departments will continue to exist.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Therefore, a university can be seen as a composition of departments, whereas departments have an aggregation of professors.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In addition, a professor could work in more than one department, but a department could not be part of more than one university.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Composition is usually implemented such that an object contains another object.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In aggregation, the object may only contain a reference or pointer to the object (and not have lifetime responsibility for it).
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Sometimes aggregation is referred to as composition when the distinction between ordinary composition and aggregation is unimportant.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In Microsoft's Component Object Model, aggregation means that an object exports, as if it were their owner, one or several interfaces of another object it owns.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Formally, this is more similar to composition or encapsulation than aggregation.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] However, instead of implementing the exported interfaces by calling the interfaces of the owned object, the interfaces of the owned object themselves are exported.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] The owned object is responsible for assuring that methods of those interfaces inherited from IUnknown actually invoke the corresponding methods of the owner.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] This is to guarantee that the reference count of the owner is correct and all interfaces of the owner are accessible through the exported interface, while no other (private) interfaces of the owned object are accessible.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Composition that is used to store several instances of the composited data type is referred to as containment.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Examples of such containers are arrays, associative arrays, binary trees, and linked lists.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In UML, containment is depicted with a multiplicity of 0..* or 1..*, indicating that the composite object is composed of an unknown number of instances of the composed class.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Objects can be composed recursively, and their type is then called recursive type.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Examples includes various kinds of trees, DAGs, and graphs.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Each node in a tree may be a branch or leaf; in other words, each node is a tree at the same time when it belongs to another tree.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In UML, recursive composition is depicted with an association, aggregation or composition of a class with itself.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] The composite design pattern is an object-oriented design based on composite types, that combines recursive composition and containment to implement complex part-whole hierarchies.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] In this example, the primitive (non-composite) types `int`, `enum Employment` and the composite array type `char[]` are combined to form the composite structure `struct Person`.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Each `struct Person` structure then "has an" age, name, and an employment type.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] C calls a record a struct or structure; object-oriented languages such as Java, Smalltalk, and C++ often keep their records hidden inside objects (class instances); languages in the ML family simply call them records.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] COBOL was the first widespread programming language to support records directly; ALGOL 68 got it from COBOL and Pascal got it, more or less indirectly, from ALGOL 68.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Common Lisp provides structures and classes (the latter via the Common Lisp Object System).
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Arrays were the only composite data type in Algol 60.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] For ALGOL 68 only the type name appears to the left of the equality, and most notably the construction is made – and can be read – from left to right without regard to priorities.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Fortran 77 has arrays, but lacked any formal record/structure definitions.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Ada 95 brought OOP concepts through tagged types (the equivalent of a C++ class), Ada 2012 added support for substitution verification through class-wide contracts.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] FORTRAN 90 updated and included FORTRAN IV's concept called `NAMELIST`.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] Common Lisp provides structures and the ANSI Common Lisp standard added `CLOS` classes.
[src:bevy-engine/object-composition] For more details about composition in C/C++, see Composite type.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:bevy-engine/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
